        Scrap stopped what he was doing and looked at me with a puzzled stare.  Had it finally hit him that he pawned off his free strip club tickets to help this case?  Or, was he wondering what the perplexed look was on my face?"Chief, you okay?" Scrap asked as he waved his monkey paw from left to right in a blessing-like fashion.<br/><br/>"Thanks Brian.  I'll get back to you." I said into my cellphone as I pressed the 'hang-up' button.<br/><br/>"Hello Chief, anybody in there?" Scrap asked again.<br/><br/>"Hold on a second, chimp boy." I responded as I dialed Reese's cellphone number.<br/><br/>"Hello!  This is Reese speaking." came a familiar voice on the other end of the conversation.<br/><br/>I cleared my throat.<br/><br/>"Reese, it's Chief.  I was thinking about the offer you made at dinner, and I agree that we need to be brought in as contractors to finish up this investigation." <br/><br/>I apparently caught Reese off guard.<br/><br/>"Really?  Okay, I'll make a few calls.  I've already explained the situation to our CFO and CEO.  They were receptive to the idea.  I'll email you an agreement for your reimbursement." Reese said.<br/><br/>"Great.  I need you to do one more thing for me." I began.  "I need you to work with your human resources manager and get me a copy of some personnel files." <br/><br/>"What?" Reese replied.<br/><br/>"I'll explain later.  I really need to review them." I said as I rattled off some employee names.  <br/><br/>We ended our phone conversation.<br/><br/>I collected my thoughts for a moment and typed some additional notes into my powerbook.  Keeping a good timeline of events is essential in any investigation.<br/><br/>"Yo, this is bothering me something fierce." Scrap announced as he motioned for me to take a look at the laptop screen.<br/><br/>"What's up?" I asked as I took a seat next to Scrap on the floor.<br/><br/>"I grabbed the workstation image that Brian provided.  Would you believe that the thing is as weak as the demo machine install CD?  It's Windows 2000 Professional, underpatched, underprotected and just plain ridiculous on every level.  There's not even a password assigned to the local Administrator account!!!" Scrap exclaimed with a painful expression on his face.<br/><br/>"That brings me to my next issue.  How many of these types of attacks have we seen since we started working together?" Scrap asked.<br/><br/>I rolled my eyes.  <br/><br/>"A lot.  I can't even count them.  Why?" I responded.<br/><br/>"Dude, in every single instance where we have investigated some type of evilware, the author always takes credit for his work.  Always.  Period.  There is no credit anywhere in here except for the distribution method, which is credited to b3nd3r." Scrap said as he scrolled through our string dump.<br/><br/>"I considered that." I said.  "But we could be dealing with a total amateur here." <br/><br/>Scrap shrugged his shoulders.  "True, boss.  But even amateurs like bragging rights.  This just isn't kosher for some reason." Scrap responded as a growling noise escaped his stomach.<br/><br/>"Evidently our stomachs are in agreement on two things.  One of them is lunch.  Let's go!" I said as I made a beeline for the door.<br/><br/>We were at the tail end of a couple of delicious rueben sandwiches when I felt my phone vibrate.  After a few napkins wipes and licking of fingers, I answered my call.<br/><br/>"Chief."<br/><br/>"Hey, it's Brian.  I tracked down Weed's machine, and you're not going to believe our luck." Brian exclaimed.<br/><br/>"Surprise me." I joked as I motioned for Scrap to join me as we walked back up to our room.<br/><br/>"It's still plugged in and running on his desk.  Apparently nobody, myself included, thought to disconnect the darned thing.  The screen is locked and none of our usual passwords work, including the Administrator password.  For whatever reason, Weed wasn't logged in to our Windows domain - he's logged in to the machine as a local Administrator." Brian said.<br/><br/>"Did you try just hitting enter with a blank password?" I said with a grin.<br/><br/>"A WHAT?" Brian replied in high-pitched voice.<br/><br/>"Just hit enter on the password field." I suggested.<br/><br/>"Uh, hold on." Brian replied as he put his cell phone down on his desk.<br/><br/>A loud series of key mashings could be heard in the background, and then Brian picked up his phone in a hurry.<br/><br/>"You know, I know you're good and all, but how THE HELL did you know the password was blank?" Brian demanded.<br/><br/>"Ancient Chinese secret." I replied.  I then explained to Brian about Scrap's discovery of the blank Administrator password on the CD image.  <br/><br/>Scrap and I entered our room and immediately woke our laptops from sleep mode.<br/><br/>"Alright, I've been schooled today.  What do you want me to look for on this box?" Brian asked.<br/><br/>"I'm emailing you a CD image.  The CD contains several tools.  I'll include a text file explaining the details, but basically I need you to use the 'pslist' utility to dump out running process information, use 'fport' to map out processes to ports in use, and then I need the standard Windows info dump including network config, user listing, etc.  You'll need a blank floppy, because my directions will tell you to direct the output of the commands that you'll be running from the CD onto a floppy disk.  Clear?"<br/><br/>I could hear Brian scribbling on a piece of paper.<br/><br/>"Got it Chief.  Be back with you in a few." Brian said as he hung up.<br/><br/>I rattled off an email to Brian and enclosed the tiny utility CD image along with some instructions.<br/><br/>*DING*<br/><br/>I had received a new email message from someone named Mary Baggins.  Her email signature indicated that she was the Human Resources Director at SST.  <br/><br/><i><br/>Chief:<br/><br/>Our employee files are electronic, so I have dumped them into PDF documents and attached them to this email.  This information is confidential, please treat as such.<br/><br/>Regards,<br/>Mary<br/></i><br/><br/>I opened the first PDF document and rubbed my eyes not once, but twice. <br/><br/>"Scrap." I said without taking my eyes off of the document.<br/><br/>Scrap was focused on his laptop.<br/><br/>"SCRAP!" I said as I knocked on the surface of the desk in front of me.<br/><br/>Scrap peered over my shoulder at the employee folder.<br/><br/>"Oh, cool!  Weed's personnel folder.  Was he busted for smoking in the bathroom?" Scrap joked.<br/><br/>I scrolled up within the document and used the screen-zoom function of Mac OS X to enlarge the employee photo.<br/><br/>"You... have... got... to be... sh..." Scrap trailed off.<br/><br/>I couldn't have said it any better myself.
    </div>    
    <div class="spacer"></div>
